description.narrative: By 2023, national and sub-national health system and service providers have improved capacity to deliver quality MNCH interventions., which contributes to Adolescent Health And Nutrition, Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Early Childhood Development, Immunization, Maternal And Newborn Health, Maternal And Newborn Health (Covid), Supply And Logistics. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023 pregnant women, mothers, newborns and children under the age of 5 years have increased equitable access to and the use of quality health and nutrition services, especially in the north-eastern provinces and among marginalized groups, including during emergencies.

description.narrative: Despite the onset of COVID-19, UNICEF's technical and financial support contributed to the continuity of essential health services, and improved equitable access to quality MNCH interventions for women and children under 5, particularly in the north-eastern provinces. This was achieved by supporting Government on COVID-19 Infection, Prevention and Control at national level and in targeted provinces, as well as continued health systems strengthening and capacity building of health workers on neonatal care, immunization, integrated community outreach, health screening and referral. However, challenges and bottlenecks remain, including high health staff turnover and persistent low coverage in high risk communities. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:21/08/2020
